\description{
\code{TaskMultiBlock()} is a factory that returns the appropriate mlr3 task type
for a multi-block analysis:
\itemize{
\item \link[mlr3cluster:TaskClust]{mlr3cluster::TaskClust} subclass for unsupervised use (\code{task_type = "clust"}),
\item \link[mlr3:TaskClassif]{mlr3::TaskClassif} subclass for supervised classification,
\item \link[mlr3:TaskRegr]{mlr3::TaskRegr} subclass for supervised regression.
}

The underlying task always stores a named \code{blocks} mapping as task metadata
(including \code{extra_args} for task conversion) and exposes three convenience
methods:
\itemize{
\item \verb{$block_features(block = NULL, materialize = FALSE)}
\item \verb{$block_data(rows = NULL, blocks = NULL, as_matrix = FALSE)}
\item \verb{$overview(rows = NULL, blocks = NULL, include_target = TRUE)}
}

This design follows the mlr3 task hierarchy: supervised and unsupervised
tasks live on different branches, so the package uses a factory plus thin
task-type-specific subclasses instead of one monolithic class.

\code{as_task_multiblock()} accepts either a flat backend plus a block mapping, or
a named list of aligned blocks which are flattened automatically with stable
\verb{<block><sep><feature>} column names.

\code{task_multiblock_synthetic()} provides a packaged 3-block toy data generator
for unsupervised, classification, and regression examples.

\code{task_multiblock_breast_tcga()} and \code{task_multiblock_potato()} are optional
dataset adapters for the \code{mixOmics::breast.TCGA} and \code{multiblock::potato}
